Understanding How Your Electrolux Washer Works
Electrolux washers stand apart from many brands with their advanced design philosophy focused on efficiency, performance, and fabric care. These premium appliances incorporate several distinctive features and systems that require specialized knowledge for proper diagnosis and repair.
Most Electrolux models utilize front-loading technology that tumbles clothes through a shallow pool of water, creating excellent cleaning while using significantly less water than traditional top-loaders. Their unique wash system combines tumbling action with spray rinses and recirculated water for exceptional cleaning performance.
Many models feature the innovative Perfect Steam™ technology that releases steam from the bottom of the wash tub, helping to remove tough stains without pre-treatment. This system works alongside the exclusive LuxCare™ wash system that provides thorough cleaning and rinsing through advanced sensors and wash actions tailored to different fabric types.
The sophisticated control systems in Electrolux washers manage everything from water temperature and levels to precise spin speeds and specialized cycles. These computerized controls interface with multiple sensors that continuously monitor conditions inside the washer and adjust operation accordingly.
Understanding these specialized components helps explain why Electrolux washers require technical expertise for proper diagnosis and Electrolux washing machine repair service. When problems arise, identifying which part of this integrated system has malfunctioned is crucial for effective solutions.
Common Electrolux Washer Problems and Their Causes
Mechanical and Operation Issues
Despite their premium engineering, Electrolux washers may occasionally experience mechanical problems:
Spin Cycle Failures: When the washer fills and washes but won't spin or drain, this typically indicates issues with the door lock, drive motor, control board, or drive system components. Electrolux's advanced motor technology requires specific diagnostic approaches when spin problems occur.
Drum Movement Problems: If the drum won't turn during agitation or spin cycles, potential causes include worn drive belts, motor control issues, or problems with the sophisticated direct drive system found in many models.
Loud or Unusual Noises: Knocking, grinding, or scraping sounds during operation often indicate specific mechanical issues such as worn bearings, foreign objects caught in the pump, or problems with the drive system. Different sounds point to different components requiring attention.
Door Lock Malfunctions: Electrolux washers have sophisticated door locking mechanisms that prevent opening during operation. Problems with these systems can prevent cycle initiation or completion, requiring specialized troubleshooting.
If your Electrolux washer is experiencing mechanical or operational problems, our washing machine repair service technicians can identify the specific components requiring attention.
Water and Drainage Problems
Water-related issues with Electrolux washers typically manifest in several ways:
Leaking: Water puddles around your washer may stem from several sources:


Damaged door gaskets or boot seals


Worn or loose water inlet hose connections


Pump or hose failures within the machine


Cracked dispenser drawers or housing


Drain hose improper installation or damage


Drainage Issues: When water remains in the tub after cycles, potential causes include:


Clogged drain pumps or blocked pump filters


Kinked or clogged drain hoses


Foreign objects trapped in the drain system


Faulty pump motors


Control system issues affecting drain commands


Fill Problems: Washers that won't fill properly may have:


Water inlet valve failures


Pressure switch malfunctions


Control board issues


Clogged inlet screens restricting water flow


When your Electrolux washer experiences water or drainage problems, professional diagnosis ensures the correct component is identified and repaired.
Control Panel and Electronic Issues
Electrolux washers feature sophisticated electronic controls that can develop several distinct issues:
Unresponsive Buttons: Touch controls may become unresponsive due to control board issues, moisture intrusion, or connection problems between the user interface and main control board.
Error Codes: Electrolux models display specific codes to indicate problems:


"E11" indicates water fill issues


"E13" signals water leak detection


"E21" relates to drainage problems


"E35" indicates pressure sensor malfunctions


"E5x" codes point to various motor and drive system issues


Display Malfunctions: Screen elements may go blank, show scrambled information, or fail to illuminate properly when button functions still work.
Cycle Interruptions: Programs that stop mid-operation often indicate sensor issues, water level problems, or main control board malfunctions.
For persistent error codes or control panel issues, professional washer repair service ensures the correct component is identified and replaced.
Cleaning Performance Issues
When your Electrolux washer runs but clothes aren't getting clean, several factors may be responsible:
Water Temperature Problems: Issues with water heating elements or temperature sensors can prevent proper cleaning, particularly in cycles designed to remove stains or sanitize items.
Detergent Dispensing Failures: The sophisticated dispensing systems in Electrolux washers may develop clogs, mechanical failures, or timing issues that prevent proper detergent distribution during cycles.
Spin Speed Irregularities: Inadequate spinning leaves clothes too wet and may indicate control problems, motor issues, or load-sensing malfunctions.
Drum Movement Limitations: Restricted tumbling action due to overloading, motor control issues, or mechanical problems can prevent proper agitation needed for cleaning.
These performance issues often result from specific component failures rather than general wear and tear. Our technicians can identify and resolve the root causes of cleaning performance problems in your Electrolux washer.
Try These Steps Before Calling for Electrolux Washer Repair
Before scheduling professional service, several troubleshooting steps might resolve minor issues:
1. Reset the Control System


Disconnect power for 1-2 minutes (unplug the unit or turn off the circuit breaker)


Restore power and attempt a normal cycle


For persistent issues, consult your owner's manual for specific reset procedures


2. Check for Obstructions or Blockages


Inspect the drain pump filter (typically behind a small access panel on the lower front)


Remove any coins, buttons, or debris that might be causing blockages


Verify the drain hose isn't kinked or clogged


3. Verify Proper Installation


Confirm the washer is level in all directions (critical for Electrolux front-loaders)


Ensure all shipping materials were removed during installation


Check that the drain hose is installed at the correct height


4. Inspect for Visible Leaks


Examine door gasket for tears, debris, or deformation


Check water supply hose connections for tightness


Look for water accumulation under the washer or around the dispenser drawer


5. Test Different Cycles


Try running a simple rinse and spin cycle to isolate performance issues


Note any error codes that appear during operation


Test if the problem occurs on all cycles or just specific ones


Regular washer maintenance service can prevent many common problems and extend the life of your Electrolux appliance.

Error codes persist after basic troubleshooting


Water leaks continue after verifying connections


The washer won't advance through cycles properly


Spin or drain functions fail consistently


Unusual noises persist or worsen

Keep your washer running smoothly with these maintenance practices specifically designed for Electrolux models:


Run the Clean Washer cycle monthly – Use washer cleaner specifically designed for high-efficiency front-loaders


Leave the door ajar between uses – Prevents odor-causing mildew growth in the door seal


Clean the door gasket regularly – Wipe down the rubber seal and remove any trapped debris


Empty pockets before washing – Small items can cause serious damage if they enter the pump or drain system


Clean the detergent dispenser monthly – Remove and rinse thoroughly to prevent buildup


Check and clean the drain pump filter quarterly – Remove lint and debris that could restrict drainage


Use HE detergent exclusively – Regular detergent creates excessive suds that can cause performance issues

full_content.content: Spin Cycle Failures: When the washer fills and washes but won't spin or drain, this typically indicates issues with the door lock, drive motor, control board, or drive system components. full_content.content: Keep your washer running smoothly with these maintenance practices specifically designed for Electrolux models:
full_content.attributes: {"class":"text-gray-500 text-sm md:text-md font-normal leading-6 font-montserrat text-left my-2"}

full_content.content:
Run the Clean Washer cycle monthly – Use washer cleaner specifically designed for high-efficiency front-loaders


Leave the door ajar between uses – Prevents odor-causing mildew growth in the door seal


Clean the door gasket regularly – Wipe down the rubber seal and remove any trapped debris


Empty pockets before washing – Small items can cause serious damage if they enter the pump or drain system


Clean the detergent dispenser monthly – Remove and rinse thoroughly to prevent buildup


Check and clean the drain pump filter quarterly – Remove lint and debris that could restrict drainage


Use HE detergent exclusively – Regular detergent creates excessive suds that can cause performance issues

self.__next_f.push([1,"## What to do if your washing machine is leaking?

One of the most common causes of a washing machine water leak is cracked or damaged fill hoses. Examine the fill hoses for cracks or damage and signs of leaking.

## Look for excessive suds

self.__next_f.push([1,"The pressure switch regulates the amount of water in the tub, ensuring each cycle runs smoothly and efficiently. In this article, we’ll take a closer look at how the water level pressure switch works, why it’s essential, and how it impacts your washing machine’s performance.

---

![washing-machine-water-level-pressure-switch](//images.ctfassets.net/e0821f6q5nel/6gOI1x17VOR28oI2XUuNL3/5828e492dca9d2ecdc5f6bdd8272eacf/washing-machine-pressure-switch-image.png)

## What is a Water Level Pressure Switch?

The water level pressure switch is a small but critical part of a washing machine’s control system. It senses the water level in the washer tub and sends signals to the machine’s control board, dictating whether it should stop or continue filling the tub. This sensor is typically a small round component located inside the machine, with a long, thin air tube connected to the bottom of the washer tub.

The pressure switch serves as the washing machine’s “eyes” on the water level, ensuring the machine uses just the right amount of water for each load. Using too much or too little water can affect washing efficiency, so the pressure switch helps maintain the correct balance.

---

## How Does a Pressure Switch Work?

The water level pressure switch works by detecting the air pressure changes in the washer’s air tube as water fills the tub. Here’s a breakdown of the process:

* __Air Tube Connection:__ The water level pressure switch is connected to the bottom of the washer tub by an air tube. As the tub fills with water, it compresses the air inside this tube.
* __Air Pressure Build-Up Moves the Pressure Switch Diaphragm:__ As more water enters the tub, the air in the tube gets more compressed, increasing the air pressure within the tube. The air pressure pushes up on the sensing diaphram inside the pressure switch.
* __Pressure Switch Activation:__ When the air pressure reaches a certain point to indicate the tub is full, it pushes the diaphragm up against an electrical switch contact that stops the filling process by shutting off electrical current to the water fill valves. This pressure level is calibrated to correspond with the desired water level for the washer.
* __Signaling the Control Board:__ When the washer has an electronic control board, once the switch detects the appropriate pressure, it sends a signal to the washing machine’s control board to stop filling the tub. 
* __The Pressure Switch Resets During the Drain Process:__ The switch remains in a “closed” position while the machine continues with the wash cycle. It then resets during the drain routine for the next water fill.

This air-pressure system is both accurate and reliable, helping the machine avoid underfilling or overfilling the tub.

---

## Types of Water Level Pressure Switches

Different washing machines use various types of water level pressure switches depending on their design. Here are the common types:

* __Mechanical Pressure Switches:__ These use a physical diaphragm that moves when air pressure builds up. This movement opens or closes electrical contacts, sending signals to the control board.
* __Electronic Pressure Sensors:__ Some modern washing machines use electronic sensors that measure air pressure with more precision, providing more accurate water level control. An electronic washer water level pressure sensor (also called a water level pressure transducer) works in a similar manner to a water level pressure sensor but a transducer creates an electronic signal instead of activating an internal switch in the component. As the washer fills with water, air in the sensor air tube pushes up on the diaphragm and moves a rod or piston inside of a core in the transducer to create an electronic signal that is sensed by the control board to control water level in the washer tub. The electronic control board stops filling the washer and advances to the wash cycle when it senses that the washer tub is full based on the signal from the water level pressure transducer.
* __Variable Water Level Sensors:__ These are designed for machines with multiple water level settings. They can detect specific pressure changes, enabling various levels based on load size and cycle type.

Regardless of the type, each switch follows the same general principle of measuring air pressure to control water levels accurately.

---

## Why is the Water Level Pressure Switch Important?

The water level pressure switch is essential for multiple reasons:

* __Prevents Overflows:__ By stopping water intake at the correct level, the pressure switch helps prevent overflows and potential water damage.
* __Saves Water and Energy:__ The switch ensures the washing machine only uses the amount of water necessary for each load, conserving water and energy.
* __Enhances Cleaning Efficiency:__ Correct water levels are crucial for optimal washing performance. Too little water can lead to ineffective cleaning, while too much water can dilute detergent, reducing its effectiveness.

### Symptoms of a Faulty Pressure Switch

## What to Do When Your Top-Load Washer is Leaking Water

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/I5JJOxkUcjA?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

**The problem:** 

You notice water on the floor of your laundry room. Answer these questions before scheduling a washer repair service call:

Are all four feet of your washer on the floor? Are the legs properly installed? If they are, see if your dryer is making the same sort of noise. If it is, your floor could very well be the issue.

We hate to even suggest that you didn’t press power — ’cause how embarrassing would that be?

### 3. Is there a delay button?
Some washers have a delay feature. You may have pressed that button inadvertently. Press stop twice to cancel any delay.

### 4. Is the lid closed all the way?
Again, some washers won’t function if the lid isn’t tightly closed.
